<br>
The gnoll pup listened to the dying cry of Fippy and slunk off into the darkness outside Qeynos. <br>
<br>
They were everywhere – the adventurers, the spellcasters, the deathdealers. The gnoll pup was the last of his brood, the only living child of a litter of eight. The rest had been cut down long before by the swords of men. <br>
<br>
The pup was undernourished; scouts were sent out for food but few ever returned. And since the humans had begun invading Blackburrow, since they’d cut off the stout trade and essentially gutted any economy the gnolls ever had, starvation had become rampant. <br>
<br>
A human spellcaster stood before him, suddenly, emerging from the dark. The gnoll pup and the mage stared at each other for just a second. Then the caster’s hand began to glow. The gnoll pup, his mother’s last child, bared his teeth and charged, one last desperate action before the darkness came… <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
King Crush sat on his throne, his head in his massive, scarred hands. <br>
<br>
Outside, he heard his soldiers dying. He heard the screaming, his men calling out his name, dying in his honor, dying for this pitiful little grove. Nothing more than a stream and a small stone tower, some slave pits that yielded little more than poor quality silver now and then… <br>
<br>
Outside his window, he heard the cry that spelled his doom. <br>
<br>
&quot;The throne room is camped!&quot; A harsh elven voice cried. By the gods, they were fighting over which of them would kill him. <br>
<br>
The dark elf put a cold hand on Crush’s shoulder. He held his blade at the ready. <br>
<br>
&quot;We’ll take a few of them with us. By the gods, we’ll take a few of the bastards with us,&quot; he said, then sighed. &quot;I didn’t want to die here.&quot; <br>
<br>
*** <br>
<br>
All about him, mad halflings, massive humans, soldiers of all kinds ran about. Goblin heads rolled like pebbles in the sea on the floor of Runnyeye. <br>
<br>
One lone knight held off the pass, his trusted bastard sword held at the ready. He could see the green blood of his kin on the blades of the adventurers as they confronted him. <br>
<br>
And he saw, in their eyes, not hatred but greed: they were eyeing his sword. And they would kill him for it gladly. <br>
<br>
The goblin knight saluted them, outnumbered, outskilled, and out of time. <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
In the darkness of Toxxulia Forest she found her brother, his tiny kobold corpse still smoldering from some wizard’s bolt. <br>
<br>
She rolled him over, touched his muzzle, brushed closed his eyes. <br>
<br>
The kobold runt was half-blind, the result of poison in the water supply put there by cruel men. Rumor had it they came from all over the world to invade the Warrens, came by the hundreds to hunt her people, a people already sick and deranged and dying from the face of the planet. <br>
<br>
A shield smashed against her back, stunning her; she rolled slowly to look up at the eyes of her killer, a man of dark skin and steely eyes. She barely felt the blade plunge into her chest, but with her last breath she reached for him, for vengeance… <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
The froglok soldier. looked at the spear pinning him to the ground, watched his life’s blood drizzle into the mud. <br>
<br>
It was a good life, he thought fuzzily. Never got to leave this forsaken swamp, but it was a good life nonetheless. <br>
<br>
I could have seen the world, he thought. If only the world didn’t see my homeland as a hunting ground. <br>
<br>
He felt himself fading away just as the dark shape reappeared over him, not big enough to be a troll, but just as fierce, just as cruel <br>
(human)<br>
as any barsher or shadowknight. <br>
<br>
The figure drew a skinning knife, and suddenly the froglok soldier knew, understood, that death would not arrive fast enough for him. <br>
<br>
-Lest Ravenfolly<br>
