<br>
Ye said ta tell tales o' other critters perspectives if we had some, an' well. I don' know much o' critters save one, an' that be unlucky cantankerous dwarves so here's ye go.<br>
<br>
***<br>
He focused solely on the opponent before him, an unatural zombie animated from beyond the grave, a blight to all that was decent and good. His picks drove home time and time again ripping the undead automaton apart, bit by bit.<br>
<br>
Suddenly throughout the Estate of Unrest a great call was heard...<br>
<br>
&quot;TRAIN!&quot;<br>
<br>
Damn gnomes, always bragging about their newfangled contraptions of clockwork and steam. He would not let the shout distract him from his purpose, this blight of smelly undeadness would fall before him, looking at the gnomish machine could come later.<br>
<br>
Victory was almost his, the undead was nearly torn to bits, just a few more true strikes with his trusty picks would rid NOrrath of yet another abomination.<br>
<br>
Suddenly he was surrounded by the death screams of elves and gnomes and a human or two. Not even allowing this to distract him his only concern was the destruction of his foe.<br>
<br>
Pain lanced through him as something struck him from behind. Daring a look he let out a horrifed gasp. A small army had ammassed behind him. Hags, massive skeletons, an angry dwarven ghost, mummies, ghouls and of all things a large hand?<br>
<br>
Where the hell was that gnomish train now when he needed it? A swift moving engine would really come in handy to get him outta this one. Eyeing the dead gnomes on the ground he decided the undead horde had probaly ambushed the train and claimed it for themselves. Damn his luck.<br>
<br>
Before he could blink they were upon him. An instant later he was standing naked outside of Kaladim, saved by the grace of Brell though not understanding why Brell's penance for his aid always involved him running across the world naked as the day he was born.<br>
<br>
After running across the drafty area known as Dagnor's Cauldron (holding a branch over his parts for modesties sake) he finally made it back into Unrest....<br>
<br>
to be greeted by a ghoul, a bony bartender, 3 undead monks and a werebat to boot.<br>
<br>
the attack from the ghoul left him paralyzed, unable to move.<br>
<br>
&quot;TRAIN TO ZONE!&quot; sounded across the estate<br>
<br>
Well good fer them he thought, sounds like the gnomes had recaptured their clockwork engine and were hightailing it out of there with it before the undead hijacked them again...<br>
<br>
He then remembered his predicament and looked back to the werebat and company. Something in the werebat's eye told him he was in for more than a leg humpin.<br>
<br>
Soon the sound of Brell's voice filled his mind as the Duke of Below spoke the words to transport him bare-buttedly to safety, a curious chant it was...<br>
<br>
&quot;LOADING PLEASE WAIT&quot;<br>
<br>
****<br>
<br>
Aye, sometimes the tables are turned an' the hunter becomes that hunted.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=lest>Lest</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 142<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/21/02 12:38:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ... more prey thoughts</span><hr size=1> (/ooc: Thanks for the feedback, ideas and additions, everyone. I came up with a few more while reading your posts, thought I'd add them -- and Madrain, I'm really not that depressing a person <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I'm just really fond of tugging on heartstrings.)<br>
<br>
They chose him because he was the fastest young orc in Crushbone. He had always run; as a boy he wished he'd been born something less stout, less clumsy, less ugly. <br>
<br>
But he could run like the wind. <br>
<br>
The messenger made it through Faydark unharmed, dodging the elves and their various traps. But he could smell them in Butcherblock, sense their quiet shadows as soon as he ran through the pass. <br>
<br>
There was more than one bounty on his head. <br>
<br>
But he could run. <br>
<br>
The first arrow struck him in the calf. The boy kept running, the pain flaring up into his skull. <br>
<br>
Then the second arrow struck, between his shoulderblades. Suddenly breathing became agony. <br>
<br>
And the arguing began. <br>
<br>
Rangers appeared from all over, bows in hand; they were confronting a pack of  elvish knights. <br>
<br>
&quot;The pack belongs to the paladins, dirtwalker,&quot; said one of the knights. <br>
<br>
&quot;That is a Faydark's Champions arrow in his back, good sir. The kill is mine.&quot; <br>
<br>
The boy fell to his knees, but kept crawling, dragging himself along the path... <br>
<br>
And looked up at the waiting axe of a dwarven soldier. <br>
<br>
&quot;Bounty er no bounty, orc, you've run through the wrong kingdom this night...&quot;<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Aviaks long ago lost the ability to fly; they still talked of the ability in children's tales, and mythology said that a great king would one day arise again, one who could fly, and bring the aviaks back to their former glory. <br>
<br>
But for now all they had was their small town, a harmless place far away from the featherless ones. Buried in the plains of Karana, doing no one no harm... yet still they come. They come to hunt. <br>
<br>
The young mother tucked her children into their beds for the night. Aviaks no longer fly but they still take to the heights, still roost high above the ground. They still hide their children in the sky. <br>
<br>
She felt rather than saw the wizard's bolt as it struck the platform beneath her. Then she smelled the smoke. <br>
<br>
The young mother stepped from her small hut to see all escape cut off by flames, all hope gone... <br>
<br>
She looked at her children. She looked at the ground far below. And she could hear in her mind the sounds of their cries as they burned. She refused to let that happen. <br>
<br>
She quickly roused them from their beds and led them outside, away from burning walkways. <br>
<br>
&quot;We're going to fly, children,&quot; she said softly. &quot;Like in the old stories. Tonight we'll all be able to fly.&quot;<br>
<br>
And to escape the pain, they flew. As best they could. <br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Once upon a time Quillmane knew other Pegasi. They flew like squadrons of demi-gods. <br>
<br>
But their time was drawing to a close, hunted by griffons for food and men for other things. Still Quillmane remained, a tribute to her race. <br>
<br>
But man still needed those other things, and as the Pegasi dwindled, the hunters came looking for Quillmane. <br>
<br>
She spent her days dodging magi, who longed for her death like no others. But these silly robed fools could not track her, and had to rely on the luck of fools to catch her. <br>
<br>
Quillmane was too smart for that. <br>
<br>
But then came the others, the trackers, the mercenaries. The people who would care nothing for Quillmane's life or death, if only her wings were not so valuable... <br>
<br>
The last Pegasi on Antonica lay bleeding, full of arrows, her red, red blood staining her white, white plummage. She whinnied softly as the hunter backed away. <br>
<br>
Then the magi knelt down beside her, a knife in his hand. He looked suddenly heartbroken. <br>
<br>
&quot;The beauty I destroy in this damnable quest for power,&quot; he whispered, unaware that it was the last earthly sounds Quillmane would hear.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubakanome.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bakanome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 338<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/21/02 1:15:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Don't mind me..</span><hr size=1> Nagafen sighed deeply, his cavernous mouth spraying a burst of flame into the air.  He heard the last of his loyal giants fall, plunging to the floor with a spray of dirt and fire.  'They come for me now,' he thought.<br>
<br>
He watched with a look of dread the group of fighters filter through into his personal prison, his lair.  <br>
<br>
Many had come before, and when they were foolish enough to announce their intent and strike out at him in their lust for opportunity and greed, he had been able to slay them.  <br>
<br>
He knew now, though, that the force stood before him was more than sufficient to kill him.  &quot;Lord Nagafen!  We are here to see an end to your reign of terror!&quot;  'What reign of terror?' he thought angrily.  'I'm imprisoned here, those are the words of someone trying to justify his own bloodlust and greed.  There is little I can do to prevent my demise.  All I can hope is that I send a few of them to hell with me.'<br>
<br>
The fire dragon reered up, making his bulky, bruised and battered form, weary from the constant combat he had undergone since his discovery by those little beings as frightening as possible.  His opponents were unintimidated, confirming the futility of his situation.<br>
<br>
