<br>
 -Do not tell me you are keeping us here in hope he is alive- barked Drogik, his tone angered<br>
 -He is my blood. Bragnar would have survived. He must have survived. Blood is strong.-<br>
 -Did you not see them wipe out the jailer? Did you see how Rikfeer got slaughtered? By Frolon Zek, didn't you see them kill the howlers, each one of those greedy monsters fighting over the pieces of wicker armor? They are making short work of any of us!-<br>
 -Then how come we still are alive? And we still have Bear Paw to protect us...-<br>
 -I implore you, my liege, Bear Paw will not be enough. We must run to the mountains. As for those furless.... you know who you can summon, it should be far enough to destroy those bastards.-<br>
 -Aye, but we_<br>
<br>
 The shrieking sound of a deflagration stopped the barks right in the king's throat. Their barriers didn't hold against the invaders... and already were they entering the lair.<br>
<br>
 Erudites, either in armor or wearing long flowing robes, pale humans, elves and dwarves, and even one of tghose towering monsters they called an ogre, all rushed in, their steel and spells meeting the first wave of kobold defenders.<br>
 Blood, fur, bits of metal flew all over in the place. Gragnar grabbed slowly his impressively heavy Naginata, the air moaning as the blade cut through it.<br>
<br>
 -Bear Paw! Charge the tall one! Shamen, slow the warriors!-<br>
<br>
 Gragnar was observing the situation, barking orders as the invaders progressed into the lair. For a wound inflicted to those strangers, a kobold was falling.<br>
 Bear Paw was fighting the ogre, his massive claws pounding on the monster's armor,slicing through it's fleshes.But where the ogre had metal plates to protect him, the mutant kobold had but his leather and fur; leather and fur wich didn't prevent the monstruous blade from killing Bear Paw in one, mighty blow. Where he fall, though, did the Bat Lord intervene, starting a desperate fight against the wounded ogre.<br>
<br>
 Otherwise did the fight start to turn into their advantage. THe ennemy knights were not used to sucha resistance nor such a number, and some had to retreat. The chants of the shamen, especially those of Drogik, saved many lives in the fury of this battle.<br>
<br>
 Soon enough though did everything change. In a distant spot of the battle were kobold slaughtered mercilessly, an impressive brute covered in a kobold's fur doing ravages among Gragnar's clan. The king readied himself to challenge this opponent, seemingly worthy of fighting him.<br>
<br>
 But the old kobold's heart was definitely shattered down as truth hit him. The beast he was about to fight, slashing elders and guards alike, or cursing them with spells of the darkest magic, was but his own son Bragnar, the kobold prince; his eyes were misty, as if covered by a veil of fog... and behind him stood a tiny being, one Gragnar learnt to know as a gnome, shouting what sounded like orders to the young prince.<br>
<br>
 -gragnar!- shouted Drogik, seemingly horrified y what he, has well, saw. -You have to stop him! He is too much of a danger for the clan!-<br>
 -Doom you shaman, this is my sonm! my one and only offspring!-<br>
 -Will five minutes of his life be worth the clan's existence??- barked fiercely the high shaman, his stare locked into the king's eyes.<br>
 -Help me stop him.... but spare his life, friend... i beg you- yapped the king, the weight of the world over his shoulders.<br>
<br>
 Bragnar didn't wait for the king and shaman to be ready. The young kobold rushed toward the king, his claws meeting the cold metal of the kobold's naginata. And then did the king notice the multiple wounds on his son's fur, the numerous stains of dried blood, as well as the tears drenching his face's fur. Blue sparks flew around the young heir, his moves seeming greatly slowed; gragnar thanked Drogik in thought for the help, while trying to pin his son down on the ground.<br>
<br>
 -Bragnar, BRAGNAR! Tis I, your father! Stop this madness, son!-<br>
<br>
 &quot;Kill him, you stupid kobold! Kill this idiiotic fleabag, i order you!&quot; shouted frantically the gnome, his hands weaving the thin threads of power that linked his mind to the prince's body.<br>
<br>
 -F... ath..er... sorry....- growled softly the prince, fighting his own body to articulate such words.<br>
 To ponctuate those was the prince's hand suddenly surrounded by a dull and dark aura, as if all light was sucked in the kobold's palm. Understanding the imminent threat, the king as well called on his dark power, his hand illuminated by the same evil forces. Both their hands met each another, cluthing at one another in a desperate struggle of strength, the prince trying to hit Gragnar with his dark touch while the king simply tried to counter his son's attack. But where the prince had to use both arms, the king only used one, his other hand holding his weapon tightly.<br>
<br>
 -Gragnar! Put an end to this nonsense now! If you are killed, we are all doomed!- madly growled Drogik while fighting one of the strangers, countless gashes opened already in the old shaman's pelt<br>
 -Damn you and your descendancy ever, Drogik! He is my son!- desperatly barked the king tears starting to stream softly as he knew the only thing left to do.<br>
<br>
 -King.... fa... father.... please...-<br>
<br>
 This time was it the prince, his eyes imploring the king, begging him to put a stop at those countless hours the prince had spent slaughtering his own kind, feeling his own body festing upon his kin's blood against his will, and now attacking the one that gave him birth... it was too much, way too much, for the prince to seek survival anymore.<br>
 A tear fell from his eyes, and in a yap did he say goodbye to his father, his hand's dark aura diseappearing in a final act of free will.<br>
<br>
 The naginata found his heart.<br>
 <br>
 The prince died instantly, painlessly.<br>
 <br>
 King Gragnar howled with pain, sadness, anger, hatred, his mind exploding under those past days' pressure. His free arm was holding his son, tight against him, and even in such a moment could he decipher the words from those doomed surfacers.<br>
<br>
 &quot;Look at this monster, barking it's victory against his own kind&quot;<br>
 &quot;Those beasts are really better wiped out.... there is no way one could find any good in them, by Tunare's light!&quot;<br>
 &quot;Pfa, how can thing so stupid claim being organized and intelligent...&quot;<br>
<br>
 It was way too much. The king charged toward the gnome, his naginata plunging thoward the tiny chest in an attempt to slice the puny foe in two, while the enchanter started glowing with a blue eerie light.<br>
<br>
 Pain rose from the mighty blow.<br>
<br>
 Not from the one delivered by the king, wich never landed, but from the one he was dealt by Drogik, in the back. Fighting his sufferings enough to turn on himself, Gragnar saw his old friend's claws covered in blood, his eyes veiled as were the ones of Bragnar... after his son, it was his childhood friend that had to attack him... but this time was it all finished... it was the end... of Gragnar... of the Warrens clan...<br>
<br>
 In a last effort, the king's paw reached for the gnome, a flash of the darkest light distorting the puny body violently as Gragnar called upon his last strengths. At least did he have revenge... Frolon Zek... have mercy...<br>
<br>
 The king's eyes felt heavy... He was so tired, so tired from all those fights. The clan was decimated, the last thing he saw being the Lorekeeper, Roggik, killed while he tried to run away, all the warrens' kobolds knowledge lost forverer along with his life.<br>
<br>
 Darkness sound fell upon the king's world.... his breath grew shallow, and stopped.<br>
<br>
 And to accompany him in the afterworld were those last words he heard, in this foreign language those strangers spoke.<br>
<br>
 &quot;So, who has got loot on the cold iron, fellas?&quot;<br>
