&quot;And so I said to him, stop it, you're acting like a silly tree elf!&quot;<br>
<br>
Humorless laughter escaped from the lips of the Koada'dal paladin.  He didn't think the other guard was funny at all, and was merely being polite.  In fact, he mused in his mind, he never really liked him all that much anyway.  He loathed to think they were even of the same Mother, much less chosen to follow in the same paths of service to Tunare.  <br>
<br>
But thus is the life of a guard, you can choose your profession, but you cannot choose who will join you.<br>
<br>
As the annoying, unfunny guard walked to the edge of the bridge, he abruptly stopped, staggered for a second, then took off running.<br>
<br>
&quot;Good&quot;, he mused, &quot;That keeps him out of my hair for a while.  I've had enough of his games for one night&quot;.<br>
<br>
The frail, starchy paladin adjusted his armor so that it looked neat and proper, and maintained an almost still position as he kept watch over the bridge.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>~time passes~</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The pristine silence of this guard of Northern felwithe was interrupted by the sound and feel of something glancing off of his armor.  He could not discern what it was that had been lobbed at him, but it had been deflected by the ornate steel he wore on his shoulder.  He took off running in the direction of the force, ready to discipline his undisciplined partner over his latest attempt at humor.<br>
<br>
Nothing could prepare him for what lay around the corner.  A small puddle of blood, and a furious mix of metal and elf parts.  A dented helm, a broken blade, arms were they shouldn't be, no legs where there should.  And all around this massacre, were the denizens of evil.<br>
<br>
And ogre, wielding a gigantic axe, grinned at him fouly, like a child with a new toy.  A slim mage, with her elemental the size of a minotaur.  Some clerics of the most vile Innoruuk, whose visages made his very soul tense and angry.  And there were more, but he not could discern their forms from the shadows.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>&quot;GUARDS!&quot; </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
He cried out, but it was too late.  He was too far from his brothers-in-arms to call for help: He had fallen for the trap in the same way his partner had.  He was no smarter, he was no better.  His ego badly damaged, his body trembling with fear, the guard lifted his sword and plunged towards the closest villain.<br>
<br>
The hands of the mage began to shimmer.  The air became warm.  She then smiled and pointed, and the force of evil was upon him.<br>
<br>
Soon the two guards would share a common resting place.  Places would be more accurate.  For parts of them would stain the ivory walls of their great city, and the rest would feed the belly of a vile Troll.<br>
